It is extra challenging for the lower body, including the quads, glutes, and hamstrings. It can be performed for time or reps in any fat-loss or athleticism-focused circuit or workout.

benifits: Serious abdominal activation and burn
Targets the six-pack muscles, but also the obliques and hip flexors
Great for variety if you've been doing standard V-ups
extra.short_desc: The knee-in to V-out is a bodyweight abdominal exercise performed on the floor. It is similar to both the reverse crunch and the V-up exercise, but combines elements of both. It primarily targets the muscles of the rectus abdominis, or “six-pack” muscles. It can be performed for reps or time, either as part of an ab-focused workout or as a component of a circuit workout.

benifits: Encourages proper squat form and depth with an upright torso
Momentum from the squat powers the weight through the toughest part of the press
Allows you to press more weight than a strict standing military press
Full-body training that challenges the lower body, as well as the shoulders, arms, back, and core
Cleaning the kettlebells to the rack position trains the hips, core, and back muscles
extra.short_desc: The single-arm kettlebell thruster is a popular kettlebell movement that combines a kettlebell front squat with a kettlebell press. It is preceded by a clean at the start of each set, and you can perform a clean between each rep if you choose. It can be trained in traditional strength or muscle-building rep ranges, in circuit or fat-loss training, or as part of a kettlebell combination or complex.

benifits: Cardiovascular and muscular challenge even with no added weight
Demands greater coordination and shoulder strength than traditional bear crawls
Challenges the shoulders, chest, core, legs, arms, and back
extra.short_desc: The bear crawl push-up is a variation of the bear crawl hold with a push-up added. It adds an extra coordination and shoulder challenge to an already intense full-body movement that targets the cardiovascular system as well as a wide range of muscle groups, the shoulders, core, and legs in particular. It can be done as a full-body warm-up, or as part of a bodyweight circuit or flow.

benifits: Builds muscular strength and endurance in the hamstrings, glutes, and quads
Works core strength to maintain balance and a neutral spine
Great dynamic warm-up before strength training
Great component of a fat-loss or conditioning circuit workout
extra.short_desc: The gorilla squat is a bodyweight sequence that combines two reverse lunges and a bodyweight squat. It could also be performed with dumbbells, kettlebells, or other weights. It targets most of the muscles of the lower body, including the quads, glutes, and hamstrings. It can be performed for time or reps in the lower-body portion of any workout.

benifits: Full-body power training without special equipment
Works the quads, glutes, hamstrings, core, and shoulders
Great alternative to the barbell snatch
extra.short_desc: The dumbbell hang snatch is an explosive exercise that builds full-body power and targets the muscles of the hips, back, and shoulders. Performing the movement from the hang position, rather than from the ground, emphasizes explosive hip and upper-body power. It can be performed for low reps with a focus on power and speed, or for higher reps to build muscle or as part of a metabolic conditioning circuit.

benifits: Challenges most of the muscles of the upper body, as well as the hips and glutes
Significant time under tension and cardiovascular challenge
Can be trained in rep ranges for strength, size, or conditioning
extra.short_desc: The kettlebell bent-over row to clean is a combination kettlebell exercise that targets many of the muscles of the upper body including the lats (latissimus dorsi), biceps, shoulders, and core. It also strengthens and trains power output of the lower body. It can be done for reps or for time as a strength or muscle-focused complex, or in circuit-style training for conditioning or fat loss.

benifits: Builds muscular endurance and strength in the lower and upper body
Extra coordination challenge beyond traditional sprawls
Cardiovascular challenge that also builds explosiveness, balance, and coordination
Requires no equipment
extra.short_desc: The surfer sprawl is an explosive bodyweight exercise that targets multiple muscle groups across the upper and lower body. It is similar to a burpee, but instead of jumping at the top, you end in a "surfer position," alternating sides with each rep. It can be performed for time or reps in any fat-loss or athleticism-focused circuit or workout. The surfer position offers a unique way to challenge the body by staying in a low position rather than standing up after the plank.

benifits: Cardiovascular and muscular challenge even with no added weight
Greater challenge to coordination and shoulder strength than traditional bear crawls
extra.short_desc: The bear crawl donkey kick is a more advanced version of the bear crawl exercise that adds a donkey kick. It adds an extra coordination and shoulder challenge to an already intense full-body movement that targets the cardiovascular system as well as a wide range of muscle groups, the shoulders, core, and legs in particular. It can be done as a full-body warm-up, in short bursts for power or circuit training, or for longer durations as cardiovascular conditioning.

benifits: Builds strength in the lower and upper body
Challenging to chest, triceps, shoulders, and obliques
Combines a high-intensity movement with a strength movement
Serious cardiovascular challenge and calorie burn
extra.short_desc: The southpaw sprawl with push-up is a full-body movement that combines elements of a plank and a sprawl, with the addition of a push-up. It also has a rotational component, with a jumping leg-cross and torso twist in a straight-arm plank position. It is a challenging move that trains balance, core strength, and many muscle groups, making it work well in a time-efficient bodyweight circuit workout.

benifits: Great move for strengthening the hips and glutes
Challenges and fortifies the core and upper back
Burns a lot of calories in a short amount of time
extra.short_desc: As the name suggests, the dumbbell skier takes the motion of skiing and replaces the poles with dumbbells. The hip and torso motion are similar to a kettlebell swing, as are the muscles it targets, including the hamstrings, glutes, upper back, and grip. However, unlike the traditional kettlebell swing, the arms are outside of the knees. This movement can be performed for time or for reps, but is usually performed for relatively high reps, such as 8-12 sets per rep or more, as part of a fat-loss or athleticism-focused circuit or workout.

benifits: Challenges the legs, core, back, and arms even with relatively light weight
Full-body conditioning and coordination challenge
Great way to make arm training more athletic
Surprising cardiovascular challenge
extra.short_desc: The dumbbell crusher is a dumbbell complex that combines a squat with a dumbbell curl, followed by a triceps press. It targets the legs, glutes, biceps, shoulders, and triceps in a single sequence, making it a great way to burn serious calories and hit a lot of muscles in a short period of time. The upper-body movements will determine the amount of weight you can effectively use.

benifits: Only requires one set of weights, but works the chest, shoulders, biceps, triceps, back, grip, and core
Doing push-ups on dumbbells may be more comfortable on wrists than doing them on the floor
Forces the core muscles to work seriously hard to stabilize throughout the sequence
Boosts the heart rate and creates a cardiovascular challenge during strength training
extra.short_desc: The dumbbell push-up row combines pressing, rowing, and core stabilization into a single sequence. It's popular in time-efficient strength and muscle-building workouts.

benifits: Builds muscular strength and endurance in the hamstrings, glutes, quads, and abductors
Works core strength to maintain balance and upright position
Great dynamic warm-up or finisher to a leg workout
Challenges the muscles to work through the tension and continuous movement
Requires no equipment
extra.short_desc: The thigh killa is a challenging lower-body bodyweight exercise that builds muscular endurance with a series of hops and bodyweight squats. It can be performed for time or reps, usually in a circuit workout or as a lower-body finisher.

benifits: Forces the core to stabilize repeatedly
Requires no equipment
Surprisingly challenging to shoulders and lats
Can help someone “feel” a plank more than static holds
extra.short_desc: The plank up is a variation of the plank that involves transitioning between an elbow plank and a sphinx-style pose with the hips on the ground. It targets the muscles of the core but is also challenging to the upper back and shoulders. It can be performed for time or reps in any bodyweight workout or during the core-focused portion of any workout.

benifits: Powerful training for the rectus abdominis or "six-pack" muscles, as well as the obliques and deep core
Both dynamic core training and anti-rotation training as the core stabilizes while the upper and lower body move
Balance challenge from the ball further amplifies ab activation
Also challenges muscles of the shoulders, back, and hip flexors
extra.short_desc: The medicine ball pike is a dynamic abdominal exercise performed with the lower legs balanced on a medicine ball. It is similar to a stability ball pike, but is more difficult due to the lower height and smaller size of the medicine ball. It can be performed for reps or time in any ab-focused workout, or as part of a medicine ball or bodyweight circuit workout.

benifits: Isometric hold builds strength in the abdominals
Strengthens the hip flexors
Engages lower-body muscles, especially the quads
extra.short_desc: The hollow-body alternating knee-to-chest is a core exercise that involves bending the legs while holding the hips and shoulder blades off the ground. It targets the rectus abdominis or "six-pack" muscles. It can be performed for time or reps in the ab-focused portion of any workout.

benifits: Burns a ton of calories and raises core temperature
Can be a warm-up, part of a circuit, or a workout all its own
Improves coordination and athleticism
extra.short_desc: Jumping rope is classic conditioning exercise that is popular with everyone from children to boxers to CrossFit athletes. It targets many different muscles, including the calves, glutes, shoulders, and upper back, and is great for everything from fat loss to improving overall athletic performance.

benifits: Strengthens the chest, triceps, and shoulders
Builds core strength and lower-body explosive power
Cardiovascular challenge that also builds explosiveness, balance, and coordination
extra.short_desc: The frog kick to push-up is a full-body, high-intensity exercise combo that blends a lower-body jumping motion with a push-up. It targets both the upper and lower body and can work as part of a dynamic warm-up or any fat-loss or athleticism-focused workout.

benifits: Full-body power training without special equipment
Works the quads, glutes, hamstrings, core, and shoulders
Great alternative to the barbell snatch
extra.short_desc: The alternating dumbbell snatch is an explosive exercise that builds full-body power and targets the muscles of the hips, back, and shoulders. Performing it by alternating arms gives each arm the chance to recover, allowing you to do a greater amount of quality work. It can be performed for low reps with a focus on power and speed, or for higher reps to build muscle or as part of a metabolic conditioning circuit.

benifits: Builds strength and muscular endurance in the quads, as well as the glutes and hamstrings
Works core strength to maintain position and keep a neutral spine
Demands flexibility and mobility of the hip flexors
extra.short_desc: The bouncing lunge is a bodyweight movement targeting the quads. It can be performed either for time or reps, and is often included as part of a fat-loss or athleticism-focused circuit workout.

benifits: Increases upper-body and lower-body strength
Increases core strength, as well as full-body coordination and balance
Trains shoulder extension and stability
extra.short_desc: The front kick-through is a full-body movement that involves moving the legs from a bear crawl position to a balanced one-legged stance. It is commonly performed for reps or time in bodyweight circuits and animal-style flows, but can also work on its own or as part of a dynamic warm-up or mobility sequence.

benifits: Activates and strengthens the abs, in particular the rectus abdominis or “six-pack” muscles
Strengthens the hip flexors in addition to abs
Easy to progress by adding weight or performing on a decline bench
extra.short_desc: The sit-up is a popular bodyweight exercise focused on the abdominal muscles. It has also been used as part of military, tactical, and scholastic fitness tests for many years. It can be performed for time or reps, with the feet anchored or free, on flat ground or a bench.

benifits: Strengthens the muscles of the abs, including the deep core and rectus abdominis or “six-pack” muscles
Builds hip flexor strength
Can help build up to long-duration L-sits and other advanced core exercises
extra.short_desc: The seated leg lift is a bodyweight exercise targeting the muscles of the core and hip flexors. It can be performed for time or reps in the core-focused portion of any workout.

benifits: Simple way to add weight to lunges when body weight is too easy
Strong isometric contraction of both the core and upper back
extra.short_desc: The kettlebell front rack lunge is a dynamic leg and core exercise in which a lifter performs lunges while holding a single kettlebell in the front-racked position. It is a unique coordination challenge, but also challenging to the musculature of the abdomen, lower body, shoulders, and upper back. It is most commonly performed for higher reps, such as 10-15 reps per side, or for time. It can work in circuit-style workouts, as well as in muscle or strength-focused workouts.

benifits: Strengthens the shoulders, upper back, and core
Being able to rotate the weight while pressing can be more shoulder-friendly than using a straight bar
Greater muscular and skeletal loading than a single-arm military press
The double clean before a press strengthens the glutes, hips, and back
extra.short_desc: The double-kettlebell shoulder press is a popular movement in strength and muscle-focused kettlebell workouts. Each set is started by cleaning the weights up to the rack position. The double press can be trained in traditional strength or muscle-growth rep ranges (e.g., 5x5 or 8-12 reps per set), or in circuit-style fat-loss training or kettlebell complexes.

instructions: Attach bands to the bar that are securely anchored near the ground. You may need to choke the bands to get adequate tension.

Use a box of an appropriate height for this exercise. Load the bar to a weight that still requires effort, but isn't so heavy that speed is compromised. Typically, that will be between 50-70% of your one rep max.
Position the bar on your upper back, shoulder blades retracted, back arched and everything tight head to toe. This will be the starting position.

Builds strength in the back, biceps, and shoulders
Great carryover to the Army's ACFT leg tuck test
Great way to "sneak" core training into strength training
extra.short_desc: The chin-up crunch is an exercise targeting the core and overall upper-body strength. It combines a chin-up with a knee raise or crunch to give extra emphasis to the core.

benifits: Teaches the most difficult portion of a Turkish get-up
Can use a heavier weight than during a full Turkish get-up
Trains shoulder and core strength and stability in multiple planes of motion
More ab-focused than a full Turkish get-up
extra.short_desc: The half Turkish get-up is a kettlebell movement that focuses on the first portion of the Turkish get-up exercise. It is often taught as a precursor to the full Turkish get-up, but is also a valuable abdominal and shoulder exercise in its own right. It can be performed for reps or time, either in lower rep ranges for strength or higher rep ranges for technique practice or conditioning.

benifits: Targets multiple parts of the abs
Allows you to train in lower strength-focused rep ranges
If performed hanging, can improve grip strength and overhead shoulder mobility
extra.short_desc: The hanging oblique crunch an abdominal exercise that targets both the rectus abdominus or “six-pack” muscles, and the oblique muscles. It can be performed hanging from a bar, or if grip strength is a limitation, by placing the elbows in ab straps. If hanging from a straight bar is uncomfortable to the wrists or shoulder, you can also perform them hanging with a neutral grip (palms facing one another)

benifits: Teaches proper bracing and core tension
Can be made easier by bending legs and/or arms
Can be made more difficult by straightening legs and/or arms
More difficult than planks
Builds core strength that carries over to lifting and athletics
extra.short_desc: The hollow-body hold is an isometric exercise that increases strength and stability in the core muscles. It is common in gymnastics training, CrossFit training, and as a core tension and bracing drill for lifters and athletes of all types. It is performed for time and can be performed as an activation drill prior to lifting, as part of a circuit, or as equipment-free core training anytime.

benifits: Strengthens the abs and hip flexors
Emphasizes the lower part of the rectus abdominis or "six-pack" muscles
Holding the position on the bars is serious work for the upper body and core
extra.short_desc: The parallel bars knee raise is a bodyweight exercise that targets the abs. It is performed on parallel bars, starting in the top position of a dip. Knee raises are often performed for moderate to high reps, such as 8-12 reps or more, as part of ab-focused training.

benifits: More difficult than bodyweight knee tucks
Stability challenge from the ball forces the abs to work harder to stabilize
Draping back over the ball between reps can increase the stretch on the abs
extra.short_desc: The BOSU knee tuck is a dynamic abdominal movement performed on a BOSU ball or other stability training device. It primarily targets the rectus abdominis or "six-pack" muscles of the core. It can be performed for time or reps as part of an ab-focused workout or a circuit involving body weight or the BOSU ball.

benifits: Great way to load abs with weight that can be tracked and increased over time
Greater range of motion than a traditional sit-up or crunch
Weighted ab training can increase core definition in addition to strength
extra.short_desc: The kneeling cable crunch is a popular core isolation exercise using a rope attachment and cable stack while kneeling on the floor. It primarily targets the rectus abdominus or "six-pack" muscles, but also strengthens the deep core muscles. It is most commonly performed early in an ab workout, usually in moderate to high reps like 8-12 reps per set or higher.

benifits: Great way to load abs with weight that can be tracked and increased over time
Cable provides constant tension on the targeted muscles
Focuses strictly on the abs without worrying about balance or stability
extra.short_desc: The kneeling cable oblique crunch is a popular core isolation exercise using a rope attachment and cable stack while kneeling on the floor. It primarily targets the obliques and rectus abdominus or "six-pack" muscles, but also strengthens the deep core muscles. It is most commonly performed for moderate to high reps like 8-12 reps per set or higher.

benifits: Maximizes force transfer through the legs, core, and arms
Powerful rotational core training
Trains coordination and power simultaneously
extra.short_desc: The landmine twist is a rotational abdominal movement performed utilizing an angled barbell anchored at floor level in a landmine device. It can also be performed by sticking a barbell in the corner of a room, preferably in a towel to protect the walls. It targets the deep muscles of the core, including both the obliques and the transversus abdominus. It can be done fast or slow, for time or reps, either in traditional muscle-focused rep ranges such as 8-12 reps per side.

benifits: Strengthens the abs and hip flexors
Emphasizes the lower part of the rectus abdominis or "six-pack" muscles
Holding the position on the bars is serious work for the upper body and core
extra.short_desc: The parallel bars leg raise is a bodyweight exercise that targets the abs. It is performed on parallel bars, starting in the top position of a dip. Leg raises are often performed for moderate to high reps, such as 8-12 reps or more, as part of ab-focused training. However, this difficult variation may require some time to build up to those rep ranges.

benifits: Builds strength, power, and stability in the abdominals
Engages the lower body and hips to stay in position
Cables allow for constant tension on the muscles
extra.short_desc: The cable lying twist on ball is an exercise targeting the core and obliques with the added challenge of stability to keep from losing position on the unstable surface.

benifits: Allows you to train in lower rep ranges when bodyweight twists get too easy
Weighted ab training can help the core muscles grow and look more defined
Trains the core in different planes of motion than crunches or sit-ups
extra.short_desc: The medicine ball Russian twist is a weighted version of a popular abdominal training exercise. It targets the oblique muscles, as well as the deep muscles of the core and the rectus abdominis or "six pack" muscles. It can be done for reps or time in the ab-focused portion of any workout.

benifits: Teaches many muscle groups to work together
Carries over to sports and other lifts
Burns calories and builds conditioning when done for higher reps
extra.short_desc: The medicine ball slam is an explosive exercise for developing power, strength, and speed. Muscles worked include the abdominals, legs, triceps, shoulders, and lats. The slams are usually done in rapid succession to complete one set. It can also be a component of a power or athleticism-focused circuit workout.

benifits: Allows you to train in lower rep ranges when bodyweight decline sit-ups get too easy
Weighted ab training can help the core muscles grow and look more defined
Also challenges the shoulders, serratus anterior, upper back, and hip flexors
extra.short_desc: The Otis-up is a weighted exercise focusing on the abdominal muscles and the shoulders to a lesser degree. It primarily targets the rectus abdominis or "six-pack" muscles, but also involves the obliques and deep core muscles. It is normally performed on a decline bench holding a weight plate, but can also be performed with a dumbbell, kettlebell, or other weight.

benifits: Build abdominal strength and muscular endurance
Works the upper and lower body isometrically to maintain position
Can also be performed with bands if cables unavailable
extra.short_desc: The pallof press is an anti-rotation, isometric exercise that trains core stability. It is most often seen in programs for athletes who compete in sports that test strength, power, and functional movements.

benifits: Hits every part of the core, including the rectus abdominis or "six-pack" muscles and the deep core muscles
Different stimulus than more traditional moves such as the crunch and reverse crunch
Great anti-extension core training
extra.short_desc: The reverse ab roll-out is an exercise targeting the abdominals. It's a twist on the ab wheel roll-out, and is similar to a body saw exercise, only performed on a foam roller. Instead of your arms moving and your lower body remaining stationary, your lower body moves and your arms remain stationary. Beginners may need to use a limited range of motion.

benifits: Stronger obliques carries over into any turning or bending mvoements
Promotes overall core stability
Contributes to better core aesthetics
extra.short_desc: The seated bar twist is a core exercise aiming to strengthen the obliques.

benifits: Great for working the abdominals and core, as well as the shoulders
Harder than traditional straight-arm planks because of switching between single arms for support
Can be performed by all fitness levels
extra.short_desc: The shoulder tap is an exercise targeting the abdominals and core. The basic stance matches the top of a push-up position. From there, one hand is raised to tap its opposing shoulder. A tap with each hand to each opposing shoulder equals one rep.

benifits: Strengthens the lateral musculature of the body, including the obliques and external hips
Powerful isometric contraction for the deep core muscles, including the transversus abdominis
Can be further progressed by performing with a straight bottom arm
extra.short_desc: The feet-elevated side plank on ball is a more advanced version of a traditional bodyweight side plank. The feet are balanced on an exercise ball, providing a balance challenge but also increasing the load placed upon the obliques and shoulder muscles. It is usually performed for timed holds, either one side at a time or alternating sides. If a ball is unavailable, some of the benefits of the movement can be obtained by performing side planks with the feet elevated on a couch, chair, bench, or other stable object.

benifits: Allows you to train in lower rep ranges when bodyweight V-ups become too easy
Weighted ab training can help the core muscles grow and look more defined
Increases abdominal strength, not just muscle tone
extra.short_desc: The smith machine V-up is a weighted abdominal exercise that involves pressing a weighted bar upward while performing a V-up. Performing it in a Smith machine eliminates the balance challenge of a free weight. It is usually performed for moderate to high reps in the ab-focused portion of a workout.

benifits: Intense challenge even with no added weight
Engrains cross-body gait pattern and athletic coordination
Challenges the shoulders, core, legs, arms, and back
extra.short_desc: The spider crawl is a bodyweight exercise that involves crawling on the floor with the knees outside of the elbows. It is different from a leopard crawl in that the hips are higher, and it's different from a bear crawl because the knees are wider. It can be done as a full-body warm-up, in short bursts for power or circuit training, or for longer durations as cardiovascular conditioning.

benifits: Builds core strength and stability
Serious cardiovascular challenge and calorie burn
Teaches core to brace while upper and lower body move
extra.short_desc: The spider crunch is a core exercise that begins in a straight-arm plank position and involves raising one knee toward your same-side elbow to target the obliques. It is similar to a mountain climber, but with the knees out wider. It can be performed for time or reps as bodyweight ab training or conditioning.

benifits: Building core strength and stability
Engages the low and upper back to maintain spinal stability
Cables allow for constant tension on the muscles
extra.short_desc: The cable reverse crunch is performed on the ground facing away from a high pulley, which helps target the lower abdominals specifically.

benifits: Added challenge beyond standard V-ups
Intense isometric and dynamic core work for rectus abdominis, or “six-pack” muscles, and obliques
Strengthens both abs and hip flexors
extra.short_desc: The full moon is a bodyweight exercise targeting the muscles of the abs. It is similar to a V-up, but with the added challenge of “drawing” a circle shape in the air during each rep. It can be performed for time or reps in the core-focused portion of any workout.

benifits: Builds strength and stability in the rectus abdominus
Builds strength and size in the deltoids
Can be progressed by increasing the decline angle over time or adding weight
extra.short_desc: The decline bar press sit-up is a core and upper body exercise targeting the lower abdominals and shoulders.

benifits: Strengthens the chest, triceps, shoulders, and core
Strengthens the abdominals, mainly targeting the obliques
Improves shoulder and hip stability
extra.short_desc: The push-up to side plank is an upper-body and core-focused exercise combining two popular bodyweight movements. It targets the chest, triceps, and shoulders with the push-up, and the obliques and hip external rotator muscles with the side plank. It can be performed as part of a dynamic warm-up or any bodyweight strength-training workout.

benifits: Combines isometric and dynamic abdominal training
Targets the six-pack muscles, but also the obliques and hip flexors
Great for variety if you've been doing standard hollow-body holds or knee tucks
extra.short_desc: The hollow-body knee tuck is a bodyweight abdominal exercise performed on the floor. It is similar to both the hollow-body hold and the knee tuck or reverse crunch, combining elements of both. It primarily targets the muscles of the rectus abdominis, or “six-pack” muscles. It can be performed for reps or time, either as part of an ab-focused workout or as a component of a circuit workout.

benifits: Builds grip, upper back, and core strength that can carry over into pull-ups
Teaches proper shoulder position that can carry over to a wide range of strength exercise
Activates important postural muscles
Can improve overhead shoulder mobility and stability
extra.short_desc: The active hang from bar is a static exercise that involves isometrically squeezing the shoulders into the sockets and activating the muscles of the upper back and core. It can be used to improve pull-up form or to do more pull-ups, but also has postural and shoulder health benefits.

benifits: Cardiovascular and muscular challenge even with no added weight
Engrains cross-body gait pattern and athletic coordination
Challenges the shoulders, core, legs, arms, and back
extra.short_desc: The bear crawl is a popular bodyweight crawling exercise. While it looks simple, the bear crawl is an intense full-body movement that targets the cardiovascular system as well as a wide range of muscle groups, the shoulders, core, and legs in particular. It can be done as a full-body warm-up, in short bursts for power or circuit training, or for longer durations as cardiovascular conditioning.

benifits: Increases mobility and flexibility in the hips, hamstrings, and glutes
Great dynamic warm-up before loaded squats or deadlifts
Activates the quads and hip and back muscles
extra.short_desc: The bootstrapper squat is a movement that improves mobility, muscular strength, and flexibility in the hips and hamstrings. It is usually performed as part of a dynamic warm-up for the lower body to mobilize the hips and improve squat form.

benifits: Builds and demonstrates strength and power in the glutes, hamstrings, and quads
Improves acceleration, balance, and coordination
Common in training for track, running, or football
Can be an effective "contrast" exercise paired with heavy deadlifts or squats to boost power
Requires no equipment
extra.short_desc: The broad jump is an explosive lower-body exercise. It is a common way to measure explosive hip and lower-body strength in athletes. The more explosive you are, the farther you'll be able to jump.

benifits: Helps boost thoracic mobility and overall spinal control
Requires no equipment
Can be done by people of all fitness levels
Not physically taxing; can be performed as a restorative exercise
Excellent way to limber up a stiff spine in the morning or before exercise
extra.short_desc: Cat-cow is a traditional yoga pose that is also popular in fitness and strength training. It targets spinal mobility and control of the vertebral column. It can be performed for time or reps as part of a dynamic warm-up or as a mobility or restorative exercise anytime. It can also work as part of a yoga or bodyweight sequence with other poses.

benifits: Targets the pectorals and triceps to a similar degree
Also works the deltoids, particularly the front heads
One side can’t compensate for the other, as in the barbell bench press
extra.short_desc: The close-grip dumbbell bench press puts a spin on a mainstay of workout enthusiasts worldwide. It’s a classic move for building a bigger, stronger chest. The difference here is that the dumbbells are held closer together.

benifits: Builds full-body muscular coordination and endurance
Increase strength and stability in the core, hips, and shoulders
Great for added variety to high-intensity training
Effective warm-up for training or sports that can be performed anywhere
extra.short_desc: The crab walk is a full-body exercise that has been popular in schools and gym classes for decades. It's a full-body coordination challenge that also burns serious calories, making it an excellent inclusion in a full-body warm-up or bodyweight circuit workout.

benifits: Strengthens and challenges the grip, core, biceps, upper back, shoulders, and legs
Serious cardiovascular challenge and calorie burn
Less complex to learn and perform properly than many other popular strength movements
Builds muscular coordination and mental toughness in addition to strength and muscle
extra.short_desc: The dumbbell racked carry involves carrying dumbbells for time or distance, while holding them close to the shoulders in a front-racked position. Similar to a dumbbell farmer's carry, it can be a challenging finisher to any workout, or work well in fat-loss circuit training or as an accessory movement to heavy lifts like the deadlift.

benifits: Mainly works the quads, hamstrings, glutes, shoulders, back, and core
Works the squat and overhead positions
The push-press allows for more weight to be used and enhanced power output
Serious cardiovascular challenge and calorie burn
extra.short_desc: The dumbbell clean and push-press is a full-body movement that targets both the lower and upper body. The clean utilizes the muscles of the hips, legs, glutes, back, and biceps, while the push-press utilizes the shoulders and triceps. It differs from the clean and press in that the push-press allows you to use lower-body momentum to power through the most difficult part of the press. It can be trained in low to moderate reps for strength, or for higher reps, such as 8-12 reps per set or more, for muscle building or metabolic conditioning.

benifits: Strengthens and challenges the grip, core, traps, upper back, shoulders, and legs
Serious cardiovascular challenge and calorie burn
Less complex to learn and perform properly than many other popular strength movements
Builds muscular coordination and mental toughness in addition to strength and muscle
If grip strength is a limiting factor, lifting straps can still enable you to use heavy weights
extra.short_desc: The dumbbell farmer's walk or carry is an exercise with roots in competitive strongman training, but which is also popular in CrossFit and functional training. It can be a challenging finisher to any workout, or work well in fat-loss circuit training or as an accessory movement to heavy lifts like the deadlift.

name: Total Fitness Dumbbell Isometric Row Hold

benifits: Forces the core muscles to stabilize while the upper body is moving
Trains back and grip strength, as well as hips and glutes from holding the bent-over position
Boosts the heart rate and creates cardiovascular challenge during strength training
extra.short_desc: The dumbbell bent-over row is a popular exercise to develop and strengthen the muscles of the upper and middle back, like the latissimus (lat), lower trapezius, and rear deltoids. It can work equally well in strength, muscle-building, or circuit-style fat-loss workouts.

benifits: May allow a greater stretch in hamstrings than two-legged Romanian deadlift
Great accessory movement for the barbell deadlift
Strengthens and builds active flexibility in the glutes and hamstrings
extra.short_desc: The dumbbell kickstand deadlift is a movement targeting the muscles of the hamstrings, glutes, and back. The kickstand position can help focus the stretch and contraction on each individual leg, similar to a single-leg Romanian deadlift, while presenting less of a balance challenge. It can be performed in low reps, such as 5-8 reps per set, for strengthening the posterior chain, or for higher reps for muscle growth.

benifits: Creates less torque in the front knee and better stability with the front leg as the stationary leg
The racked position forces the core to work harder to keep from rounding forward as you lunge
Helps improve hip flexibility and core stability
extra.short_desc: The dumbbell racked reverse lunge is a popular lower-body movement that targets the muscles of the quads, glutes, hamstrings, and hips. Holding dumbbells in the racked position further challenges the core and upper-back muscles to maintain posture while the lower body moves. Lunge variations are often performed for moderate to high reps, such as 8-12 reps per leg or more, as part of the lower-body portion of a workout. If this movement hurts your knees, try performing split squats instead.

benifits: Only requires one light pair of weights, but significantly works the core, back, and shoulders
Forces the core muscles to work hard to stabilize throughout the sequence
Boosts the heart rate and creates a cardiovascular challenge during strength training
extra.short_desc: The dumbbell renegade row combines rowing and core training into a single difficult movement. It's popular in time-efficient strength and muscle-building workouts, as well as in circuit-style training.

benifits: Front leg as stationary leg helps maintain stability better than forward lunges
Less torque on the front knee
Helps improve balance hip flexibility, core stability, and overall functionality
extra.short_desc: The dumbbell reverse lunge is a great single-leg movement that strengthens and builds the quads, hamstrings, and glutes.

benifits: Adds size and strength in lats and upper back
Great way to make shoulder training more athletic
Isometrically works the core and posterior chain
extra.short_desc: The dumbbell row to triceps kick-back is a dumbbell complex that combines two movements that collectively target the muscles of the lats (latissimus dorsi), upper back, and triceps. It also isometrically targets the core, hamstrings, and glutes. It is usually performed one rep of each movement at a time, although you could perform more reps of each, or increase the reps in successive rounds (e.g., 1 rep in round 1, 2 reps in round 2, etc.). No matter how you structure the sets and reps, it is a time-efficient way to hit two crucial upper-body muscles in any workout.

benifits: Builds chest and triceps size and strength
Free hand can help perform forced reps
Takes your legs out of the movement, giving all the responsibility to your core and upper body
extra.short_desc: The single-arm dumbbell floor press is a multijoint pressing exercise performed lying on the floor, either with the knees bent or straight. It has less range of motion than a regular dumbbell bench press, but still targets the chest, triceps, and anterior delts. By performing it with one arm, you can strengthen weakness on certain sides or simply use it as a way to challenge the core more during this exercise.

benifits: Full-body power training without special equipment
Works the quads, glutes, hamstrings, core, and shoulders
Great alternative to the barbell snatch
extra.short_desc: The single-arm dumbbell snatch is an explosive exercise that builds full-body power and targets the muscles of the hips, back, and shoulders. It involves lifting a dumbbell from the ground to overhead in a single movement. It can be performed for low reps with a focus on power and speed, or for higher reps to build muscle or as part of a metabolic conditioning circuit.

benifits: Builds lower-body strength and power
Improves balance
Mercilessly reveals any muscle and strength imbalances between the legs
extra.short_desc: The dumbbell step-up is a great exercise for building lower-body strength and power. The dumbbell version is better for intermediate and advanced lifters than beginners, who should begin by performing these unweighted.

benifits: Activates rotator cuffs and many muscles in the shoulders and upper back
Requires no equipment
Can contribute to improved mobility and range of motion in shoulders
Can contribute to better form on overhead work and all types of presses
extra.short_desc: The floor angel is a stretch targeting shoulder mobility and activation of the shoulder stabilizer muscles. It also targets a range of postural muscles in the upper back.

benifits: Builds stability in the shoulders and hips and strengthens the lower body
Improves overhead mobility and thoracic flexibility
Can be used as a dynamic warm-up for full-body and overhead movements
extra.short_desc: The lunge with overhead reach is a full-body bodyweight movement targeting the quads and shoulders. It has both strength and mobility benefits and can be performed one leg at a time or alternating for time or for reps.

benifits: Builds and strengthens the hamstrings
Trains knee flexion function of hamstrings
Great high-rep burnout movement or primer before strenght training
extra.short_desc: The hamstring slide is a bodyweight exercise targeting the hamstrings. Lying supine on a smooth surface, you bend your knees to pull both heels toward you. The sliding action requires a pad, cloth, or furniture sliders under the heel. These are considered more difficult than exercise ball hamstring curls, and are a great primer movement before heavy squats or deadlifts, or as an accessory movement later in a lower-body workout.

benifits: Effective stretch for the lats, shoulders, and pecs
Builds grip strength that can carry over to pull-ups and other bar exercises
Can improve overhead shoulder mobility and stability
extra.short_desc: The hang from bar is a static exercise that involves hanging from a bar by two hands. It can either be an "active hang," where you pack the shoulders and activate the muscles of the upper back, or a "passive hang," where you let the shoulders unpack and let the muscles of the upper body stretch. A passive hang may not be appropriate for all people depending on their shoulder health, but many coaches believe hanging can be healthy for the shoulders when done properly.

benifits: Teaches proper bracing and core tension
Can be made easier by bending legs and/or arms
Can be made more difficult by straightening legs and/or arms
More difficult than planks
Builds core strength that carries over to lifting and athletics
extra.short_desc: The hollow-body hold is an isometric exercise that increases strength and stability in the core muscles. It is common in gymnastics training, CrossFit training, and as a core tension and bracing drill for lifters and athletes of all types. It is performed for time and can be performed as an activation drill prior to lifting, as part of a circuit, or as equipment-free core training anytime.

benifits: Strengthens the muscles of the lats (latissimus dorsi), biceps, upper back, core, and grip
Allows you to perform pull-ups for high reps
Provides a serious cardiovascular challenge and calorie burn when done for high reps
Effective way to get into position to perform pull-up negative reps
extra.short_desc: The jump to pull-up is a bodyweight exercise that targets the muscles of the back, biceps, and, to a lesser degree, legs. It involves jumping up to a pull-up bar between reps. Similar to a push-press, the legs help power through the most difficult portion of the pull-up, allowing you to perform more reps. Jumping pull-ups are often performed for moderate to high reps, such as 8-12 reps per set or more, as an accessory to other pulling or pull-up training, or as a full-body movement in a circuit or metcon.

benifits: Builds strength, stability, and balance
Stretches and trains the adductors and abductors
Strengthens stabilizer muscles for other exercises or sports involving lateral movement
extra.short_desc: The lateral lunge is a lower-body bodyweight movement that works the quads, glutes, and hamstrings. It can also be performed holding dumbbells or other weights. It is often performed for reps as part of a dynamic warm-up or mobility routine but can also work in a circuit or other workouts.

benifits: Great dynamic warm-up
Common drill for basketball and other sports
Raises core temperature
Activates and mobilizes hips and glutes
extra.short_desc: The lateral shuffle is a common exercise in sports training and gym classes. It involves taking steps to one side and then steps to the other side. It can be performed as part of a circuit for athletes of any level, but is also a great movement for beginners.

benifits: Improves flexibility and mobility in the hips and glutes
Can relieve tension in the lower back and hips
Improved mobility in hips leads to better performance in lower-body movements
extra.short_desc: The pigeon stretch is a lower-body stretch targeting the glutes, hips, and piriformis. It is similar to the pigeon pose from yoga, but is also popular as part of dynamic warm-ups or cool-downs in strength training. It can also be performed anytime to help combat training-related soreness.

benifits: Strengthens the chest, triceps, shoulders, and core
Targets the powerful fast-twitch muscle fibers
Carries over to increased speed and strength in pressing movements
extra.short_desc: The plyo push-up is a bodyweight exercise aimed at increasing upper-body power and strength. It targets the muscles of the chest, triceps, and shoulders, and can be trained in low reps for power and strength, or higher reps for conditioning.

benifits: Stretches and strengthens all three heads of the triceps, including the long head
"Rolling" the weights overhead targets the long head specifically
May be more elbow-friendly for some people than skullcrushers
Can be done as an accessory movement or a high-rep burnout
extra.short_desc: The rolling triceps press is a dynamic triceps exercise that is popular as a bench press accessory movement among powerlifters. It can be done in traditional muscle-building rep ranges, such as 8-12 reps per set, or for very high reps of 50-100 reps per set to boost triceps size and strength. It can be performed on a bench or on the floor if a bench is unavailable.

benifits: Improved shoulder health and function
Increases core strength and stability
Teaches both retraction and protraction of scapulae, which is essential for shoulder health
extra.short_desc: The scapular push-up is an upper-body exercise aimed at increasing the stability of the scapulae and mobility in the shoulders. It is often performed as part of a dynamic warm-up before an upper-body workout, or as part of a mobility session.

benifits: Can help prepare shoulders for lifting and avoid or work through injury
Carries over into stronger and safer overhead pressing movements
Can also be done with your back against a wall
Warm-up for core and back in addition to shoulders
extra.short_desc: The bent-over scapular slide is an upper-body exercise that helps with scapular and shoulder mobility. It is commonly performed for time or reps as part of a dynamic warm-up for the upper body.

benifits: Increases range of motion in shoulders
Stretches biceps and activates upper back
Carries over to pressing movements like dips and the bench press
extra.short_desc: The shoulder extension stretch is focused on bringing more flexibility to the shoulder joint. It increases range of motion in shoulder extension, or moving the arms behind the back. It can be performed as part of a warm-up or mobility and flexibility work post-workout or anytime.

benifits: Strengthens and builds the hamstrings, glutes, and lower and upper back
Teaches coordination and moving the body as one unit
Adds a cardiovascular and conditioning challenge to strength work
extra.short_desc: The barbell deadlift bent-over row complex combines two movements to target the posterior chain. It requires using a lighter weight than you could handle for heavy deadlifts alone, but doubles down on activation in the upper back, lower back, and glutes.

benifits: Builds and demonstrates strength and power in the glutes, hamstrings, and quads
Improves speed, agility, and power output
Common in training for track, running, or football
Can be an effective "contrast" exercise paired with heavy deadlifts or squats to boost power
extra.short_desc: The tuck jump is a vertical jump, an explosive lower-body exercise that is a common way to measure explosive hip and lower-body strength in athletes. The more explosive you are, the higher you'll be able to jump.

name: 30 Shoulders Bent-Over Low Cable Reverse Fly
30 Shoulders Incline Face-Down Dumbbell Reverse Fly
30 Shoulders Incline Face-Up Straight-Bar Front Raise
30 Shoulders Seated Banded Barbell Shoulder Press

benifits: Increased overall upper-body strength
Can vary the difficulty by raising or lowering the height of the bar
Easy to perform mechanical dropsets
Great for performing hands-elevated push-ups
extra.short_desc: The Smith machine push-up is an upper-body exercise targeting the chest, shoulders, and triceps. It is similar in form to bodyweight push-ups, but with the hands on the bar of the Smith machine. This allows you to vary the height to increase or decrease difficulty, or to perform a mechanical dropset by raising the bar after hitting failure at a certain height.

name: 30 Chest Smith Machine Incline Chest Press

benifits: Builds size and muscular endurance in the quads, glutes, and hamstrings
Develops core strength and hip stability to maintain proper positioning of torso
Works muscles in different planes of motion
extra.short_desc: The 3D dumbbell lunge is a sequence of lower-body exercises that target the muscles of the glutes, quads, and hamstrings from a variety of angles. It consists of one curtsy lunge with each leg, followed by one reverse lunge with each leg. This lunge variation is most commonly performed for multiple rounds as part of a lower-body circuit or workout.

name: MetaBurn Alternating Curtsy Lunge To Squat
MetaBurn Alternating Curtsy Lunge With High Knee
MetaBurn Alternating Plank Row With Dumbbell Pull-Through
MetaBurn Alternating Plank Row With Push-Up

benifits: Builds strength and size in the shoulders and chest
Increases core strength and stability
Trains shoulder extension and stability
Greater challenge to the rectus abdominis or "six-pack" muscles than traditional sit-throughs
extra.short_desc: The alternating sit-through with crunch is a full-body movement that starts in a bear crawl position and ends with a leg kicked out to the side. In between reps, you perform a crunch. It is commonly performed for reps or time in bodyweight circuits and animal-style flows, but can also work on its own or as part of a dynamic warm-up or mobility sequence.

name: MetaBurn Bent-Over Row to Rear-Delt Raise

benifits: Simple way to increase the challenge of jump squats
Serious cardiovascular challenge and calorie burn
Builds leg muscle and power
Improves balance and athleticism
extra.short_desc: The dumbbell jump squat with rotation is a popular movement combining an explosive lower-body movement with extra upper-body loading in the form of dumbbells held in the hands. Each jump ends with the body turned 90 degrees, adding a rotational power component to the lift. It is usually performed with light weights for high reps in fat-loss and conditioning workouts.

name: MetaBurn Dumbbell Wide Squat to Rack
30 Back Standing Low Cable Bar Row
30 Back Standing Low Cable Rope Row
FYR2 Dumbbell Deadlift to Dumbbell Upright Row
FYR2 Fire Feet with Burpee Tuck Jump Drill
FYR2 Glute Bridge Dumbbell Floor Press
FYR2 Superhero Lunge Squat Clean and Press

benifits: Strengthens the chest, triceps, shoulders, and core
Increases core strength and hip stability
Engages lower-body muscles to maintain plank position
Part of the new Army Combat Fitness Test or ACFT
Can add pauses or manipulate tempo to increase difficulty
extra.short_desc: The hand-release push-up is a variation of the push-up, a popular bodyweight exercise commonly used in military and tactical physical fitness tests. It’s a movement to build upper-body strength and endurance, emphasizing the chest, triceps, and shoulders, but also working the upper back and core. This specific exercise is part of the new Army Combat Fitness Test or ACFT.

benifits: More difficult than the traditional straight-arm plank
Increased core engagement due to extra movement
Develops and strengthens core stabilizer muscles
extra.short_desc: The hand shift plank is a progression of the straight-arm plank exercise where you maintain a plank position as you shift your hands side to side. The additional movement forces the core muscles to work harder to stabilize.

benifits: Isometric hold builds strength in the abdominals
Co-contraction of core and adductor muscles
Engages lower-body muscles, especially the quads, hip flexors, and adductors
extra.short_desc: The side-lying leg adduction scissor is a dynamic core exercise that combines the isometric hold of a side-lying leg lift with leg adductions to further challenge the core and adductors. It targets multiple muscles of the core, primarily the rectus abdominis or "six-pack" muscles. It can be performed for time or reps in the ab-focused portion of any workout.

benifits: Strengthens the chest, triceps, shoulders, and core
Increases upper-body strength and core stability
Engages lower-body muscles to maintain plank position
More difficult progression of the standard bodyweight push-up
Can add additional pauses or manipulate tempo to increase difficulty
extra.short_desc: The 1.5-rep push-up is a more difficult variation of the push-up, commonly used to train for military and tactical physical fitness tests. It builds upper-body muscle and strength, emphasizing the chest, core, upper back, triceps, and shoulders.

benifits: Strengthens the chest, triceps, shoulders, and core
Targets the powerful fast-twitch muscle fibers
Carries over to increased speed and strength in pressing movements
Cardiovascular challenge that also builds endurance, balance, and coordination
Requires no equipment
extra.short_desc: The triple-clap push-up is an explosive bodyweight exercise aimed at increasing upper-body power and strength. It is an advanced exercise targeting the muscles of the chest, triceps, core, and shoulders.

benifits: Builds muscular endurance and strength in the lower and upper body
Requires core and lower back strength to keep a neutral spine during the push-up and sprinter jump
Improves explosiveness and power
Cardiovascular challenge that also builds endurance, balance, and coordination
Requires no equipment
extra.short_desc: The sprinter burpee is an explosive version of the burpee exercise that adds a sprinter jump to the top of each rep. It can be performed for time or reps in any fat-loss or athleticism-focused circuit or workout.

benifits: Explosive push-up, plyometric push-up
Targets the powerful fast-twitch muscle fibers
Carries over to increased speed and strength in pressing movements
Cardiovascular challenge that also builds endurance, balance, and coordination
Requires no equipment
extra.short_desc: The Superman push-up is an explosive bodyweight exercise aimed at increasing upper-body power and strength. It is an advanced exercise targeting the muscles of the chest, triceps, shoulders, and core that involves pressing up off the floor and lifting the hands and feet off the ground simultaneously at the top of the movement.

benifits: Works the obliques and deep core or transversus abdominis
More challenging than standard planks
Helps develop balance, focus, and body awareness
extra.short_desc: The cross-body plank march is an exercise targeting the entire core but especially the obliques. It’s more difficult than a standard plank, with the extra stabilization challenge of bringing one knee at a time off the ground toward the opposing elbow. This will increase the challenge to the core and shoulder muscles, but also present a coordination and balance challenge.

benifits: Band provides constant tension and dynamic resistance
Targets the upper chest and shoulders
Greater range of motion than barbell presses
Allows for natural shoulder and wrist rotation
May be more shoulder-friendly than barbell presses
extra.short_desc: The incline band bench press is variation of the incline press, a popular upper-body exercise targeting the upper pectoral muscles. While it can be a strength-focused movement, it is usually performed for moderate to high reps, such as 8-12 reps per set or more, as part of upper-body or chest-focused training.

benifits: Allows natural rotation of the hand
Single-sided focus allow you to target and engage the proper muscles
Sneakily difficult core work when done with heavy bands or high reps
Builds size and strength in the chest and triceps
Increased time under tension for muscles in the upper body and core
Teaches full-body tension generation from head to toe with heavy loads
extra.short_desc: The Spoto press is a variation of the popular barbell exercise the bench press that builds strength and muscle in the chest, triceps, and shoulders. It differs from the bench press in that the lifter pauses for a few seconds at the bottom of the movement before pressing the bar back up. This pause removes all momentum and increases the time under tension for the chest and shoulder muscles to help develop upper-body musculature and strength.

benifits: Builds strength and muscular endurance in the quads, glutes, and hamstrings
Works core strength to maintain position and keep a neutral spine
Demands flexibility and mobility of the hip flexors
A more difficult progression of the bodyweight bouncing lunge or spilt squat
extra.short_desc: The band split squat is a band movement targeting the quads, glutes, and hamstrings. It can be performed either for time or reps, and is often included as part of a fat-loss or athleticism-focused circuit workout. Leaning back places more emphasis on the glutes and hamstrings, while standing straight up targets the quads.

benifits: Works the legs, glutes, back, core, and hamstrings
Can work in endurance or muscle-focused rep ranges
Adds a challenge to the upper back, shoulders, and core to maintain proper posture
Dynamic tension more closely matches strength curve than freeweights
extra.short_desc: The band front squat is a popular exercise for targeting the muscles of the lower body, including the quadriceps, glutes, and hamstrings. Holding band in the racked position also works the core and upper-back muscles to maintain posture while the lower body moves. Because the tension of the band changes as it stretches, the resistance more closely matches the natural strength curve of the squat. This movement is usually performed for moderate to high reps, at least 8-12 reps per set or more. If this movement hurts your knees, try performing it with a wider stance.

benifits: Strengthens and stabilizes the core, shoulders, and hips
Excellent progression once side planks become too easy
Places extra emphasis on the adductors
extra.short_desc: The bent-knee Copenhagen hip adduction is an advanced exercise that combines the isometric stabilization of the Copenhagen plank with dynamic adductions to challenge the core stabilizers and adductors. This exercise targets the same muscles as the side plank, including the obliques, shoulders, and lateral hips, but places extra emphasis on the adductors and is more difficult than side planks on the floor. Most lifters will need to progress to this version after mastering the basic side plank or Copenhagen plank first.

benifits: May be more shoulder-friendly than either bench or overhead presses 2.Intense stabilization challenge to the core
Single-arm training focuses on each side individually, addressing potential imbalances
Band adds dynamic resistance and constant tension
extra.short_desc: The single-arm banded landmine press is an upper-body exercise that uses an angled barbell anchored at floor level in a landmine device. It can also be performed by sticking a barbell in the corner of a room, preferably in a towel to protect the walls. The band adds constant tension and dynamic resistance to the exercise. The movement focuses primarily on the muscles of the shoulders or deltoids and can be trained in traditional muscle and strength-focused rep ranges or for higher reps.

benifits: Strengthens the muscles of the lats, upper back, and core
Easy to alter grip width to provide variety and better target the upper back muscles
Effective alternative to pull-overs and cable pull-downs, especially for people with limited overhead shoulder mobility
Band provides constant tension and dynamic resistance throughout movement
extra.short_desc: The band straight-arm pull-down is a non-gym or at home variation of the straight-arm lat pull-down performed using a cable stack machine. It can either be performed in an athletic upright stance, or slightly bent over. It both stretches and contracts the muscles of the lats (latissimus dorsi) as well as providing additional activation to the other upper back muscles and the core. Because the triceps are also isometrically involved in the movement, it is usually performed for higher reps, such as 8-15 reps or more.

benifits: Forces the core muscles to stabilize while the upper body is moving
Trains back and grip strength, as well as hips and glutes from holding the bent-over position
Boosts the heart rate and creates a cardiovascular challenge during strength training
extra.short_desc: The band bent-over row is an exercise to develop and strengthen the muscles of the upper and middle back, like the latissimus (lat), lower trapezius, and rear deltoids. Bands provide dynamic resistance and can work equally well in strength, muscle-building, or circuit-style fat-loss workouts.

benifits: Distributes weights evenly around lifter's center of gravity
Can be performed in more of a squat style, making it more back-friendly than a barbell deadlift
Potentially safer to perfrom for higher reps than the barbell deadlifts
Part of the new Army Combat Fitness Test or ACFT
extra.short_desc: The low-handle trap bar deadlift is a variety of deadlift performed in a hexagonal barbell also known as a trap bar. This specific exercise is part of the new Army Combat Fitness Test or ACFT. The bar is held with a parallel (palms in) grip outside of the legs. It is biomechanically different from a barbell deadlift in that it lines up with a lifter's center of gravity, rather than placing the weight in front of their body. It activates all of the same muscle groups as conventional or sumo deadlifts, including the glutes, quads, hamstrings, lower back, lats, upper back, and grip.

name: ACFT Medicine ball overhead power throw

benifits: Build explosive power in lower and upper body simultaneously
Great carryover to strength and endurance sports
Effective even with a relatively light medicine ball
Part of the new Army Combat Fitness Test or ACFT
extra.short_desc: The medicine ball overhead power throw is an explosive exercise targeting the abdominals and hips. This specific exercise is part of the new Army Combat Fitness Test or ACFT. It can be performed for lower reps with a focus on power or for higher reps with a focus on fat loss and conditioning. It begins in a semi-squat position holding a medicine ball, which then gets "scooped" up and thrown overhead in one continuous movement.

benifits: Higher degree of difficulty than hanging leg raise
Part of the new Army Combat Fitness Test or ACFT
Can be performed anywhere with a bar to hang from
Can be the main focus of a minimalist core routine
Builds grip, hamstring flexibility, and pull-up strength
extra.short_desc: The hanging leg tuck is an exercise targeting the entire body, including the arms, upper back, abs, and hip flexors. This specific exercise is part of the new Army Combat Fitness Test or ACFT. It is performe while hanging from a bar and combines elements of a pull-up with a leg raise. Experienced lifters make these look easy, but beginners may need time to build up to sets of 8-12 reps.

benifits: Helps develop speed, power, and acceleration in athletes
Burns a lot of calories
Sport-specific training for athletes in numerous sports, including football
Part of the new Army Combat Fitness Test or ACFT
extra.short_desc: The sprint-drag-carry is a strength and endurance relay that is part of the new Army Combat Fitness Test or ACFT. It combines sprinting, reverse sled drag, side shuffle, and a farmer's carry to test overall strength and athletic conditioning. Practicing this relay as a drill is great for developing strenght, speed, endurance, and power, and can also be great conditioning work for lifters and athletes of all ability levels.

benifits: Hanging produces higher degree of difficulty than with the captain's chair or parallel bars
Builds strength in the midsection and grip
Can be performed anywhere with a bar to hang from
extra.short_desc: The alternating hanging knee raise is an exercise targeting the abs, but which also works the lats and hip flexors. Rather than performing both legs at a time, you lift one knee at a time and alternate with each rep as if marching in place. Knee raises are often performed for moderate to high reps, such as 8-12 reps or more, as part of ab-focused training.

benifits: Helps develop speed, endurance, and agility
Burns a lot of calories
Popular training drill for athletes
Develops cardiovascular fitness and sprint speed
extra.short_desc: Shuttle run training is an athletic conditioning drill that’s great for developing speed and power, as well as changing direction. It’s a favorite of football and basketball players, but it can also be great conditioning work for lifters and athletes of all ability levels.

benifits: Develops the calf muscles to add size and strength
Alter tempo or add pauses to increase intensity
Using weight allows tracking and periodization of training
extra.short_desc: The dumbbell walking calf raise is a dynamic exercise targeting the calf muscles of the lower leg, particularly the gastrocnemius muscle. It can be performed for distance or for reps.

benifits: Builds strength and size in the biceps
Increases the range of motion by pulling the arms back
The cables provide constant tension on the muscles
Serious biceps isolation if performed with strict form
extra.short_desc: The single-arm cable outward-facing biceps curl is a cable exercise that targets the biceps. It is performed standing in front of a cable machine facing away from the cable stack to increase the range of motion by fully extending the elbows. This movement is usually performed for moderate to high reps for a burn and pump as part of an arm-focused workout.

benifits: Builds shoulder strength and stability
Strengthens the rotator cuff, specifically the external rotators
Warms up the shoulder and rotator cuff
extra.short_desc: The cable 90-degree external rotation targets the rotator cuff muscles to help strengthen the shoulder girdle. It is usually performed as part of a dynamic warm-up or for therapeutic rehabilitation of the shoulder.

benifits: Builds strength and size in the biceps
Increases the range of motion by pulling the arms back
The cables provide constant tension on the muscles
Serious biceps isolation if performed with strict form
extra.short_desc: The cable outward-facing biceps curl is a cable exercise that targets the biceps. It is performed standing in front of a cable machine facing away from the cable stack to increase the range of motion by fully extending the elbows. This movement is usually performed for moderate to high reps for a burn and pump as part of an arm-focused workout.

benifits: Builds muscular strength and endurance in the hamstrings, glutes, quads, and abductors
Works core and upper-back strength to maintain neutral spine
Great dynamic warm-up before strength training
Uses lightweight equipment suitable for at-home workouts
extra.short_desc: The banded squat toe tap is a banded variation on the classic bodyweight squat, but with a lateral toe tap to add extra focus to the stabilizer muscles around the hips. It can be performed for time or for reps as part of a dynamic warm-up for the lower body, or in any lower-body portion of a workout.
